The `DropdownButton` `value` is the value of currently selected `DropdownMenuItem` or can be null if no item has been selected.

This part `items.where((DropdownMenuItem&lt;T&gt; item) =&gt; item.value == value).length == 1` from the exception means that there is no (or more than one) `DropdownMenuItem` with `value` you set for `DropdownButton` `value` (in this case `value: currentPriceProducts`).

Example:

    DropdownButton(
      hint: Text(&quot;Hint&quot;),
      value: &quot;abc123&quot;, // currently selected value - &quot;abc123&quot; or &quot;def456&quot; or null
      items: [
        DropdownMenuItem(
          value: &quot;abc123&quot;,
          child: Text(&quot;ABC123&quot;),
        ),
        DropdownMenuItem(
          value: &quot;def456&quot;,
          child: Text(&quot;DEF456&quot;),
        ),
      ],
      onChanged: (value) {},
    )

Looks like the problem here is the FutureBuilder. When you select a value, `setState()` is called and widget is rebuilt. This means that FutureBuilder is rebuilt and `listProductsPrice(currentProducts)` is called again and probably returns different values. If these values doesn&#39;t contain your selected value, you get this error.

So you could do this: Create stateful widget with your dropdown menu

    class Dropdown extends StatefulWidget {
      final String title;
      final List&lt;PriceProduct&gt; priceProducts;
    
      const Dropdown({Key key, this.title, this.priceProducts}) : super(key: key);
    
      @override
      _DropdownState createState() =&gt; _DropdownState();
    }
    
    class _DropdownState extends State&lt;Dropdown&gt; {
    
      String _selected;
    
      @override
      Widget build(BuildContext context) {
